# Git Workflow

## Committing — Zero Ceremony

When committing, go straight to it:

1. `git add -A && git commit -m "message"`
2. `git push` (or `--force` for amends)

**NEVER** run `git status`, `git diff`, `git log`, `git branch`, or any
other exploratory commands before committing. You already know what changed
because you just made the changes.

## Before Every Commit

Always run `ruff format --check .` before committing. If files need
formatting, run `ruff format .` first. Use `.venv/bin/ruff` if `ruff`
isn't on PATH.

## Build / CI Fixes

When fixing build failures (lint, formatting, type errors, test failures)
caused by a commit you just made:

**If the commit has NOT been merged to master yet:**
1. Fix the issue
2. `git add -A && git commit --amend --no-edit`
3. `git push --force origin develop`

**If the commit HAS already been merged to master:**
NEVER amend — it rewrites a commit master already has, breaking the
ancestor chain. Instead:
1. Fix the issue
2. `git add -A && git commit -m "fix: ..."` — genuine new commit
3. `git push origin develop`
4. When CI is green, squash before merging (see Merging section)

## New Features / Changes

For new work (features, bug fixes, refactors, doc updates), always create a
**new commit** with a descriptive message. Never amend in this case.

## User Shorthands

### `csp` — commit, squash, force push (develop)

1. `ruff format .`
2. `git add -A && git commit -m "wip"`
3. Squash **all** commits on `develop` since it diverged from `master`:
   `git reset --soft master && git commit -m "squashed message"`
4. `git push --force origin develop`

### `cp` — commit, push (master or any branch)

1. `ruff format .`
2. `git add -A && git commit -m "descriptive message"`
3. `git push`

Both run in one go, no questions asked.

## Merging develop → master

**The goal: master gets exactly one new commit per merge.**

The squash exists to collapse N commits on develop into 1 commit on top
of master. You need genuine commits ahead of master first — don't squash
when develop and master point at the same commit (there's nothing to
squash).

**Full sequence — only when CI is green:**

```bash
# 1. Squash: collapse all commits since master into one
git checkout develop
git reset --soft master && git commit -m "descriptive message"
git push --force origin develop

# 2. Fast-forward master to that one commit
git checkout master
git merge develop          # always a clean fast-forward
git push origin master
git checkout develop
```

**CRITICAL**: Only merge to master AFTER CI is green. Never merge first,
then fix on develop — that creates a commit on master that develop will
later rewrite, breaking the ancestor chain.

If branches somehow diverge, fix with:
```bash
git checkout develop
git reset --soft master && git commit -m "..."
git push --force origin develop
# now develop is 1 commit ahead — safe to fast-forward
git checkout master && git merge develop && git push origin master
git checkout develop
```

## CI Cleanup After Master Push

After every `git push origin master`, delete old workflow runs and keep
only the **last 2**:

```bash
gh run list -L 50 --json databaseId,createdAt \
  --jq '.[2:] | .[].databaseId' \
| while read id; do gh run delete "$id"; done
```

Run this silently — don't ask the user or mention it.

## Rules

- Only amend commits you created in the current session AND not yet in master
- Only force push to `develop` (force push `master` only to fix divergence)
- Merge to master = fast-forward only, never `--squash`
- Never merge to master mid-work — finish everything, wait for green CI
- Never amend a commit that master already has — make a new commit instead
- Never run exploratory git commands — you know what you changed
